ed Kingdom":"Chappel, Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, Anglie, United Kingdom","Chappel, City of Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Chappel, Essex, Anglie, United Kingdom"},"da":{"Abt 1534–1576":"omkring 1534–1576","1530–Male":"1530–Afdød","1533–1616":"1533–1616","1534–1576":"1534–1576","1540–Female":"1540–Afdød","1545–Male":"1545–Afdød","1554–1625":"1554–1625","1495–1545":"1495–1545","October 1554":"oktober 1554","1495":"1495","Abt 1534":"omkring 1534","1545":"1545","1534":"1534","1533":"1533","1576":"1576","1554":"1554","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","about 1553":"omkring 1553","1519":"1519","1616":"1616","1625":"1625","Chappel, Essex, England":"Chappel, Essex, England","Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chappel, City of Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom"},"nl":{"Abt 1534–1576":"circa 1534–1576","1530–Male":"1530–Overleden","1533–1616":"1533–1616","1534–1576":"1534–1576","1540–Female":"1540–Overleden","1545–Male":"1545–Overleden","1554–1625":"1554–1625","1495–1545":"1495–1545","October 1554":"oktober 1554","1495":"1495","Abt 1534":"circa 1534","1545":"1545","1534":"1534","1533":"1533","1576":"1576","1554":"1554","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","about 1553":"circa 1553","1519":"1519","1616":"1616","1625":"1625","Chappel, Essex, England":"Chappel, Essex, England","Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Chappel, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk","Chappel, City of Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Chappel, Essex, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1534–1576":"about 1534–1576","1530–Male":"1530–Deceased","1533–1616":"1533–1616","1534–1576":"1534–1576","1540–Female":"1540–Deceased","1545–Male":"1545–Deceased","1554–1625":"1554–1625","1495–1545":"1495–1545","October 1554":"October 1554","1495":"1495","Abt 1534":"about 1534","1545":"1545","1534":"1534","1533":"1533","1576":"1576","1554":"1554","1530":"1530","1540":"1540","about 1553":"about 1553","1519":"1519","1616":"1616","1625":"1625","Chappel, Essex, England":"Chappel, Essex, England","Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom","Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Chappel, City of Colchester, Essex, England, United Kingdom":"Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Abbott","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: nickname from Middle English <i>abbod</i>, <i>abbot(t)</i>, <i>abbat</i> ‘abbot’ (Old English <i>abbod</i>) or Old French <i>abet</i> ‘priest’. Both the Old English and the Old French term are derived from Late Latin <i>abbas</i> (genitive <i>abbatis</i>) ‘priest’, from Greek <i>abbas</i>, from Aramaic <i>aba</i> ‘father’. The nickname was presumably a joking reference to a person's behaviour. In the US, the English name is also sometimes a translation of a cognate or equivalent European name, e.g. Italian   Abate  , Spanish   Abad  , or German   Abt  .","History: George Abbot from Yorkshire, England, settled in Andover, MA, in 1640; he had numerous prominent descendants. George Abbott (probably not the same man) died in Rowley, MA, in 1647. Another early migrant was James Abbott, who came from Somerset, England, to Long Island, NY, in the 17th century."],"variants":[{"name":"Abate","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Italian Salvatore, Antonio, Carmelo, Carmine, Gaetano, Vito, Angelo, Canio, Rocco, Sal, Aldo, Carlo.","Italian: from <i>abate</i> ‘priest’ (from Late Latin <i>abbas</i> ‘priest’, genitive <i>abbatis</i>). It could be a nickname, perhaps given to someone who behaved in a priest-like manner, an occupational name for the servant of a priest, or it may denote an (illegitimate) son of a priest. Compare   Labate  ."]},{"name":"Abbot","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Abbott  . The spelling with one <i>-t</i> is more typically Scottish than English, and in Gaelic-speaking areas of Scotland, this is sometimes an Anglicized form of   McNabb  ."]},{"name":"Abbitt","meanings":["English: variant of   Abbott  ."]},{"name":"Abbett","meanings":["English: variant of   Abbott  ."]},{"name":"Abbotts","meanings":["English:","topographic or occupational name from Middle English <i>(atte) abbotes</i> ‘(at the, of the) abbot's (house or quarters)’, a name for someone who lived or worked at such a place, presumably a servant.","variant of   Abbott  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Thomas Abbott was born about 1534, in Bishop's Stortford, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John Abbott, was 40 and his mother, Agnes Buckland Elmyn, was 40. He married Anne Goodwyn about 1553. They were the parents of at least 1 son. In 1609, his occupation is listed as yeoman. He died in 1576, in Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 43, and was buried in Chappel, Essex, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1534–1576":"umbes 1534–1576","1530–Male":"1530–Surn